Week 3: Validating the Encounter–Alcohol Merge and Preparing the Readmission Target

During Week 3, I continued developing the data-processing workflow for connecting Social Determinants of Health information with hospital encounter data for the Kansas population data sets. I focused on the Alcohol Use domain by organizing the survey responses at the encounter level, applying dummy coding to the answer categories, and merging the resulting alcohol variables with the cleaned encounters dataset using the PatientDurableKey and EncounterKey. I also investigated duplicate merge-key errors and performed validation checks to confirm that the corrected merge did not produce conflicting alcohol-response rows.

I met with Dr. Tchoua to review progress and discuss the significance of inclusive feature generation for admission type, ensuring that hospital admissions and ED visits are appropriately captured. I also presented my dummy/one-hot encoded alcohol variables, including stratifications for high, low, never, and unknown use at the meeting with the undergrad/high school students . During the 1 on 1 discussion, I was granted flexibility to perform the 30-day readmission calculations using date-level comparisons rather than exact timestamps.

This work reinforced the importance of validating intermediate results instead of assuming that a successful line of code produced the intended output. I reviewed how the number of alcohol questions answered was calculated, checked the consistency of the dummy variables, and began preparing the next stage of the project: constructing the 30-day hospital readmission target. I also started organizing quality-control reports, sample rows, column lists, and summary outputs so the workflow can be documented and reproduced.
